##### How has diversity evolved at Baruch ?

Diversity has become a central topic in public debate across many sectors of society, including higher education. At Baruch College, diversity is not merely a slogan; it reflects the representation of students from different racial, ethnic, and gender backgrounds within our student body. 

Recalling the lawsuit against Havard University brought by Students for Fair Admissions, the case sparked a national debate about whether Asian American applicants were treated unfairly in colloge admissions, while favoring other groups. n recent years, however, admissions data show that Asian American students now represent roughly 37–41% of Harvard’s incoming classes (Classes of 2028–2029). This raises an important question: how does diversity look at a public institution such as Baruch College, and how has it evolved over time?

As of 2024, Asian students represent the largest share of Baruch's undergraduate population at 35.1% , followed by Hispanic students and White Students with 28.7% and 18.31%. One interesting fact is that Asian students makes up the largest demographic group, surpassing both White and Hispanic students. Also, gender composition was relatively balanced.

Looking at enrollment data from 2010 to 2024 provides further insight into how Baruch's demographic composition has evolved. Through this period, Asian students consistently represented the largest share of the undergraduate population, White students initially held the second largest share, but around 2015, Hispanic students surpassed them to become the second-largest group on campus. These shifts highlight how the composition of Baruch's student body has gradually changed over time.

Taken together, these long-term trends suggest that Baruch's diversity has evolved gradually rather than dramatically. The university continues to attract students from a wide range of backgrounds, and its demographic composition increasingly mirrors the multicultural characters of New York City itself.

A comparison with public universities in California provides additional context. When examining institutions with the University of California System and the California State System, we observe patterns similar to those seen at Baruch College. Between 2010 and 2024, these California institution also experience an increase in the proportion of Asian and Hispanic students and a gradual decline in the share of White students. 

In this sense, the changes observed at Baruch do not appear unusual compared with  trends at California public unversities. Utimately, these comparisons reinforce an important point: diversity in higher education evolves gradually over time as university responds to the communities they serve. At Baruch College, the changing composition of our student body reflects the dynamic and multicultural character of New York City itself.

